Description from the publisher:

It is a time of madness and horror. The Mortal Realms writhe in the grip of the Chaos Gods, whose murderous champions fight furiously to extinguish the last lights of hope. But above, the heavens roar and the sky itself is rent by searing bolts &ndash; the Stormcast Eternals, glorious warriors of celestial light, have arrived to turn back the tide of Khorne&rsquo;s murderous Bloodbound. The war has begun in earnest.

Thunder and Blood is the perfect starter set, containing everything you need to start playing games of Warhammer Age of Sigmar. It contains 44 Easy To Build miniatures from both the Khorne Bloodbound and Stormcast Eternals armies, supplied in red and gold plastic &ndash; these are a great introduction to the wider world of Citadel miniatures as a whole. Included:


     2 units of 5 Liberators each armed with Warhammers and Sigmarite Shields, including a Liberator-Prime;
     3 Prosecutors armed with Celestial Hammers, including a Prosecutor-Prime;
     3 Retributors armed with Lightning Hammers, including a Retributor-Prime;
     1 Lord Relictor armed with Relic Hammer;
     2 units of 10 Bloodreavers each armed with Reaver Blades, including a Chieftain and Icon Bearer;
     5 Blood Warriors armed with Goreaxes and Gorefists, including a Chaos Champion;
     1 Khorgorath;
     1 Bloodstoker armed with Torture Blade and Blood Whip.


Of course, you&rsquo;ll need rules and guidance in order to play games with your new miniatures &ndash; included is a 96-page softback book, packed with background and essential information on painting and playing:


     An easy to follow guide to setting up and playing games of Warhammer Age Of Sigmar, including the basic rules of movement, spellcasting and attacking, with notes and annotations explaining exactly how each phase works;
     4 Battleplans &ndash; these are scenarios that feature the included miniatures, with special instructions for setting them up, each re-creating a specific battle from the rich history of the struggle to dominate the Mortal Realms &ndash; these increase in scale from the initial few miniatures to finally fielding every one of the 44 included, easing you into larger and larger battles;
     8 Warscrolls &ndash; these contain the rules for individual miniatures, explaining how far they move, how strong their attacks are and any special abilities they may have;
     Overview and background of the Age of Sigmar, with guides to the Mortal Realms and a history of the battles between Chaos and Order that are tearing them apart;
     Simple, easy to follow guides (4 steps each!) to painting a Stormcast Eternals Liberator and a Khorne Bloodbound Blood Warrior;
     Uniform guides to 6 Stormcast Eternals and 6 Khorne Bloodbound factions &ndash; these are designed to be inspirational rather than necessarily followed to the letter, making your collection unique;
     Guides to and explanations of the various types of Citadel brushes  what they&rsquo;re used for, and how to take care of them;
     Guides to the various techniques used to paint miniatures &ndash; undercoating, basecoating, shading, drybrushing, layering and glazing are covered, with explanations of each technique and practical examples showing you their effects on; - Methods for creating evocative bases for your miniatures to stand on;
     An explanation of Technical paints, and their use in creating special effects like blood and rust;


It also contains a double-sided gaming mat, representing different areas of the Mortal Realms, 6 dice, a measuring stick, a rules reference card and a Stormcast Eternals transfer sheet: even the internal box tray doubles up as a scenery piece!

In this family friendly party game, players take turns to mime (using hand gestures and body movements only), various combinations of Animals and Ailments. The game is split across green animal cards and red ailment cards.

Players take turns to win cards by miming and guessing. Scoring in the game revolves around players successfully miming and guessing the animal/ailment COMBO:

Shout out the COMBO to win the red card:
&ldquo;a tiger that&rsquo;s scared of mice!&rdquo;
"a sleepwalking kangaroo"
&ldquo;a kleptomaniac clownfish!&rdquo;
&ldquo;a hungover hyena etc!&rdquo;

There are bonus and steal mimes available, letting you win an extra red card from the box, or steal a card from another player respectively (if you still have time left on the timer to mime these additional mimes). There is also a "Barnslig Bonus" wildcard that infers four special actions to its owner. The Barnslig Bonus can be played at any time.

マルチプル (Multiple) is a Japanese card game in which you create a "multiple" of the target number by combining digit cards. You can either play a number that is a multiple of the target card (for instance a 9 when the target card shows a 3), use two number cards as two digits (for instance 1 and 2 to form a 12), or use "+" or "-" cards to create an equation (for instance 7-1). However, you may not play a multiple that has been played by another player in the same round. The goal is to be the first player to get rid of all your cards.

&bull;&bull;&bull;

指示された数の倍数を、数字カードを組み合わせて作るゲームです。

Description from the publisher:

After London is a versatile adventure board game set in a steampunk London. Players take on the roles of "compatible" humans with extraordinary powers that race against each other or collaborate in a series of unique adventures against the game. After London, takes players through a journey in an electrifying comic book-based universe, lit by candlelight and powered by steam. Explore London, collect equipment, fight "roamers" and aliens or simply attack and sabotage each other.  Humanity&rsquo;s only hope to reveal the true story behind the "Arrival" lies with unlikely heroes. This is the story of London&hellip;

After London

Erik the Red, leader of the vikings, has decided it's time to discover America &mdash; but the vikings are lazy and in no mood to go on a long holiday trip&hellip;

The players in Viking Tourists are tribal leaders who try to gather the young and the old of the village to go and see the world. Every player builds their own sequence of vikings and the opponents' sequences as well, but without helping each other, victory cannot be achieved.

Whoever first collects all fifteen members of the village, uses all four action cards (which can set back or help opponents), and has no more cards in hand wins the game and can set sail to America.

BrazChess is a Chess-like game that combines in its design several elements found in other games of its kind (like Modern Chatranj, Makruk, Shogi and FIDE Chess) along with brand new ideas to provide a unique experience to the players.

Pieces are weaker than in FIDE Chess, but stronger than in Modern Shatranj and Makruk - so the game fits as another bridge between these games and regular Chess. Even though the game has the same number of pieces that there is in Chess (32), there is a slightly greater variety of them in BrazChess (8 against 6 in Chess). Some of the "parachuting" that occurs in Shogi is present (regarding the movement of Grand Dukes - a promoted Pawn); you'll also find different forms of capturing (suicidal attacks and the Grand Duke's Zone of Control). Also present is the concept of passing your turn.

What you need to play it:
In order to play BrazChess, you will need:
A) The rules (see Files);
B) A Modern Chess board (8x8) and Pieces (you'll need to either paint the heads or bases of two Pawns from each side, or use some other Pieces to represent the 2 Lords from each side). Note that the starting position of some pieces (like the Rooks) is different than in regular Chess;
C) 6 different pieces, coins, tokens or even checkers pieces (for the promoted Pawns aka Grand Dukes);
D) 1 tokens to represent Passing; 
E) An auxiliary board (the Duchy) or a designated space on the table.

The creation of this game was inspired by Chatranj, Modern Chatranj, Makruk, Shogi, Chess/Orthochess (FIDE Chess) and the book "Encyclopedia of Chess Variants" - by D. B. Pritchard. While it is true that there are several Chess-like games like this in the World, Chess is, itself, a variant of an older game, that was already a variant of an even older game. BrazChess, while definitely a member of the Chess family of games, has many unique features that will certainly deliver a different experience than the other games of its kind.
